241	73	14	\N	Short answer: get your routine vaccines up to date, plus hepatitis A. Depending on where in Brazil you’ll go and what you’ll do, you may also need or want yellow fever, hepatitis B, typhoid, rabies or malaria prevention. See below — and tell me your exact itinerary and vaccination history and I’ll give a tailored plan.\n\nWhat most healthy adult travelers should do\n- Routine vaccines: confirm you are up to date on MMR (measles-mumps-rubella), Tdap (tetanus-diphtheria-pertussis; booster every 10 years), varicella if no history, and annual influenza. Measles outbreaks occur occasionally — two MMR doses if not already immune.\n- COVID-19: be up to date with recommended COVID-19 vaccine doses/boosters.\n- Hepatitis A: recommended for all travelers to Brazil (single dose pre-travel gives good short‑term protection; complete the series afterward).\n- Hepatitis B: recommended for unvaccinated travelers who may have sex with new partners, need medical care, get tattoos/piercings, or have prolonged stays — consider the vaccine series.\n\nLocation- and activity-dependent vaccines / prevention\n- Yellow fever vaccine: recommended if you will visit Amazon and many interior/rural states (eg, Amazonas, Pará, Acre, Rondônia, Roraima, Amapá, parts of Mato Grosso, Tocantins and others). Not usually needed for short stays confined to large cities (Rio, São Paulo) unless you visit endemic areas. If recommended, it must be given at least 10 days before travel. Some entry/exit requirements may change, so check current travel health advice.\n- Typhoid vaccine: consider if you will eat in small towns/rural areas or stay with locals for extended time; not routinely required for short stays in major cities.\n- Rabies pre-exposure vaccination: consider if you’ll be doing outdoor/remote work, extended rural stays, or expect contact with animals. Post-exposure management is simpler after pre-exposure vaccination.\n- Malaria: no vaccine routinely recommended, but malaria occurs in the Amazon region. If you’ll visit that area, you may need antimalarial prophylaxis (choice depends on exact location). Mosquito avoidance is important.\n\nTiming and next steps\n- You said you leave in ~1 month — make an appointment with a travel clinic or your primary care provider as soon as possible. Some vaccines need multiple doses or 10+ days to be effective (yellow fever).\n- If you want, tell me: exact cities/regions to visit, length of stay, planned activities (rural/urban, rainforest, volunteer/medical work, animal contact), pregnancy or immune problems, and which vaccines you’ve already had. I’ll give a personalized list and an action plan.
