661	219	11	\N	E\nIf you need a detailed explanation for this choice: The presence of a solitary thyroid nodule with no associated symptoms and normal serum TSH levels may represent an autonomously functioning benign adenoma or non-toxic multinodular goiter. While the next steps after finding such a nodule can vary, often starting with ultrasonography is appropriate to evaluate its characteristics without subjecting the patient to invasive procedures unless there's suspicion of malignancy based on sonographic features and/or fine needle aspiration biopsy results.\n\nE) Ultrasonography of the thyroid gland - A detailed explanation for this choice: Thyroid ultrasonography is a non-invasive imaging method that can evaluate nodules in terms of size, composition (solid or cystic), echogenicity, margins, and blood flow. These characteristics help differentiate benign from potentially malignant lesions based on established criteria such as the Thyroid Imaging Reporting & Data System (TI-RADS) scores without exposing patients to ionizing radiation like in CT scans or causing discomfort with an invasive procedure like FNAB. Ultrasonography is usually performed before any intervention and can help decide if further action such as a biopsy might be needed based on the ultrasound findings alone, making it often the most appropriate initial step for management in this case of isolated thyroid nodule with normal TSH levels but unknown characteristics.
