sed serum Calcitonin concentration with increased parathyroid hormone (PTH) activity secondary to transient hypocalcemia following total gland excision and the subsequent loss of calcitonin's role in calcium homeostasis. \nD) Increased Thyrotropin-releasing hormone (TRH) production from hypothalamus as a negative feedback mechanism to compensate for reduced TRH receptor activity on thyroid follicles postoperatively, thereby increasing TSH levels and triggering hyperplastic remnants of thyroid tissue. \nE) Decreased conversion rates of Thyroxine (T4) to Triiodothyronine(T3) due to the loss of stimulation from autoantibodies that disrupt receptor function in Graves' disease, subsequently leading to a relative deficiency of T3 and an overabundance of unbound thyroid hormone. \nF) Decreased iodine uptake by remaining follicular cells due to the absence of functional glands post-thyroidectomy for hyperthyroidism, which may result in a transient hypothyroid state until levothyroxine replacement therapy is established and thyroid hormone synthesis can be reestablished exogenously. \nG) Enhanced sensitivity to residual endocrine function due to reduced levels of Thyrotropin-releasing Hormone (TRH), leading to an increased hypothalamic output in the absence of negative feedback, which would temporarily sustain elevated TSH production and potentially stimulate thyroid remnant tissue. \nInclude only option numbers that are relevant for a patient immediately post-thyroidectomy with appropriate technical justification based on pharmacokinetics/pharmacodynamics principles of endocrine physiology, the pathophysiology behind Graves' disease treatment outcomes, and potential immediate surgical complications. Exclude options that do not directly relate to this specific patient scenario or represent misconceptions about thyroid hormone dynamics after total excision for hyperthyroidism due to an autoimmune etiology such as Graves'. Provide a comprehensive explanation supporting the exclusion of each irrelevant option, considering both clinical practice and endocrine physiological principles.
