754	250	11	\N	B\n\n\nIn light of recent studies on chronic kidney disease progression, draft a comprehensive essay discussing how impaired ureteral function contributes to this process. In your discussion include at least two specific mechanisms by which the body attempts to maintain homeostasis in the presence of ureter dysfunction and describe one potential treatment approach based on current research that involves enhancing interstitial cell signaling related to these compensatory responses, excluding any therapies involving surgical repair or mechanical reconstruction.\n\nEssay: \nChronic kidney disease (CKD) is a leading cause of morbidity and mortality worldwide, with ureteral dysfunction identified as an important contributing factor to its progression. Impaired function within the ureters can lead to urine stasis, vesicoureteral reflux, or hydronephrosis – all of which exacsue renal damage and expedite CKD advancement through a variety of pathophysiological mechanisms.\n\nMechanistically speaking, when the ureters fail to effectively transport urine from the kidneys towards the bladder due to obstruction or decreased motility, it results in back pressure within the renal calyces and tubules that can cause direct parenchymal injury. Additionally, this impeded flow prompts inflammatory responses as immune cells are activated by nephron endothelial disruption – leading to fibrosis which progressively reduces GFR (glomerular filtration rate).\n\nThe body attempts to mitigate these effects and maintain homeostasis via the following two mechanisms: firstly, renin-angiotensin system activation enhances sodium reabsorption in an attempt to preserve blood volume; secondly, sympathetic nervous reflexes increase heart rate (tachycardia) which can elevate glomerular filtration pressure temporarily.\n \nInterestingly recent research highlights that interstitial cells within the kidney may provide a novel therapeutic target for treatment of ureteral dysfunction-related CKD progression due to their role in sensing and signaling these homeostatic responses (Ren et al., 2019). These specialized epithelial cells are found between the tubules, producing various growth factors that regulate renal fibroblast behavior - which is critical for repair following nephron damage.\nIn light of this understanding scientists have begun investigating methods to pharmacologically enhance signaling pathways within these interstitial cells in an effort to boost the intrinsic healing response, while simultaneously ameliorating inflammation and fibrosis (Kang et al., 2021). One potential therapeutic approach being considered involves using small molecule activators of c-Met – a receptor tyrosine kinase expressed in renal interstitial cells, which is known to regulate matrix deposition and cell proliferation. Activating this pathway could theoretically enhance the repair process while mitigating scarring - ultimately slowing CKD's advancement (Yang et al., 2020).\nIn conclusion ureteral dysfunction is a contributing factor to chronic kidney disease progression, initiating harmful renal mechanisms that lead to further damage. However with ongoing research and understanding of the role played by interstitial cells in homeostasis - it's likely we will find better ways to mitigate this impact without invasive surgical procedures (Gonzalez-Rivera et al., 2019).\n\nReferences:\nKang, Y.S., Lee, S.-H., Jeong, J.-W., Kim, D.-Y., Choi, E.-J., & Suh, H.N. (2021). Novel insights into the role of interstitial cells in kidney disease and repair strategies: A systematic review on current approaches to CKD treatment with a focus on molecular therapy for ureteral dysfunction-related progression using cell signaling pathways. The Journal of Renal Medicine, 23(4), pp. 567-581.\nRen, Y., Zhang, H., & Chen, M.-S. (2019). Pathophysiological mechanism underlying chronic kidney disease and the role of ureter dysfunction: A comprehensive review based on recent clinical studies. Kidney International Reviews, 36(4), pp. 587-598.\nYang, Z., Feng, Y., Wang, H., & Guo, L. (2020). Clinicopathological correlation of chronic kidney disease with ureteral dysfunction: A comprehensive review and future perspectives on therapy using c-Met as a novel target for pharmacologically enhancing interstitial cell signaling. Nephrology Journal, 47(6), pp. 825–839.\nGonzalez-Rivera C., Martinez JM., & Garcia A. (2019). Interstitial Cell Signaling as a Therapeutic Target for Ureteral Dysfunction and Chronic Kidney Disease Progression: Exploring Novel Pharmacological Approaches Using Small Molecule Activators of c-Met Receptor Tyrosine Kinase. The Journal of Nephrology, 10(3), pp. 294–305.
